issue.title: FX tracing improvement

repository.name: transformers
repository.description: ðŸ¤— Transformers: State-of-the-art Machine Learning for Pytorch, TensorFlow, and JAX.

issue.body:
# What does this PR do?

This PR improves significantly the way transformers models are traced by the HFTracer (`torch.fx`).
This has 2 major consequences:

- More model architectures can be supported
- When a model can be traced, the resulting GraphModule can take any input shapes out of the box (compared to what was done before where a lot of work was needed to enable dynamic axes for a given model), this is both easier and less bug prone.

Because of these changes the `symbolic_trace` signature becomes easier: 
`symbolic_trace(model: PreTrainedModel, input_names: Optional[List[str]] = None) -> GraphModule`

There is no need to specify the batch size, the sequence length or the number of choices (for multiple-choice) anymore.
The same thing can be said about the `HFTracer`, which can be instantiated exactly the same way as the regular `torch.fx.Tracer` can.

issue.title: Fix ORTTrainer failure on gpt2 fp16 training

repository.name: transformers
repository.description: ðŸ¤— Transformers: State-of-the-art Machine Learning for Pytorch, TensorFlow, and JAX.

issue.body:
# What does this PR do?

Fixes [#11279 of onnxruntime](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11279)

## Context

Optimum users reported that the mixed-precision training on gpt2 with `optimum.onnxruntime.ORTTrainer` is broken since transformers>4.16.0. After investigation, the break comes from the [removal of `float()`](https://github.com/huggingface/transformers/pull/14321/files#r912791693) in gpt2 modeling from PR #14321.

__Reproduction__

Run optimum onnxruntime training example [run_glue.py](https://github.com/huggingface/optimum/blob/main/examples/onnxruntime/training/text-classification/run_glue.py) with:
```bash
python run_glue.py \
    --model_name_or_path gpt2 \
    --task_name sst2 \
    --do_train \
    --do_eval \
    --fp16 \
    --output_dir /tmp/ort-gpt2-sst2/
```
 
__Error Message__
```
RuntimeError: /onnxruntime_src/orttraining/orttraining/python/orttraining_pybind_state.cc:752 
onnxruntime::python::addObjectMethodsForTraining(pybind11::module&, 
onnxruntime::python::ExecutionProviderRegistrationFn)::<lambda(onnxruntime::training::OrtModuleGraphBuilder*, const 
pybind11::bytes&, const onnxruntime::training::OrtModuleGraphBuilderConfiguration&)> [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : 
Type Error: Type parameter (T) of Optype (Where) bound to different types (tensor(float) and tensor(float16) in node 
(Where_201).
```
As mentioned in the error message, the forward with onnxruntime InferenceSession will fail on a node __Where__ in the graph, which corresponds to the [Where op](https://github.com/michaelbenayoun/transformers/blob/9ef5813d73b2af238e8820e117dd32415ce4c173/src/transformers/models/gpt2/modeling_gpt2.py#L206) in gpt2 modeling.

And the problem comes from the fact that after removing `float()`, during fp16 training, the inputs of Where have different dtype (one in fp32 and one in fp16), which violates the definition in ONNX and leads to the failure.

## Who can review?

@michaelbenayoun @patrickvonplaten, @LysandreJik

## Fix

Ensure `attn_weights` and `value` has the same type in exported ONNX IR.

issue.title: Add Optimum submodule support + add working Dockerfiles

repository.name: onnxruntime-training-examples
repository.description: Examples for using ONNX Runtime for model training.

issue.body:
The model scripts which were previously modified and live in this repository now live in the Optimum GitHub repo. This repo will instead hold the script and run configurations for running and comparing various models. 

Summary of changes:
* removed submodule pointing Ravi's custom branch
* added submodules for Optimum and Transformers
* changed hf-ort.py script to copy scripts from either Optimum or Transformers depending on the run configuration
* removed mentions / previous option to use CUDA 10.2 since CUDA 10.2 has been deprecated
* lowered the T5 batch size because the old batch size caused out of memory errors even on the recommended VM size
* removed scripts and requirements files that were migrated in from the last PR (now that work lives in either the Optimum or the Transformers repos respectively)
* added new Dockerfiles
     * based on PTCA image with dependencies installed on top of it
     * Dockerfile_clm is specifically for running the run_clm.py script for GPT2 because GPT2 requires a specific version of transformers

issue.title: Removed GPT2 Separate Dockerfile

repository.name: onnxruntime-training-examples
repository.description: Examples for using ONNX Runtime for model training.

issue.body:
According to this issue ([#86](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-training-examples/issues/86)) and this tracking issue ([#11279](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11279)), the GPT2 requiring transformers==4.16.0 seems to be resolved, and the separate Dockerfile was causing issues because it was missing some dependencies. Because of these developments, GPT2 no longer requires a separate Dockerfile.

Changes:
* removed if statement from the hf-ort.py script so that GPT2 is treated the same as other models
* removed mentions of the separate dockerfile and the GPT2 issue from the readme
* deleted Dockerfile_clm

I also have not been able to test this change, but at the very least, hopefully this PR can be worked off of to integrate GPT2 again and resolve the issues that Ethan flagged.
